Dialogue: 1,0:00:00.00,0:00:44.07,Tiny,,0,0,0,,{\an9\pos(1196,118)\c&H00988F8A&}VOICEOVER  //  CAPTIONS SYNCED
Dialogue: 10,0:00:00.00,0:00:03.27,Caption,,0,0,0,,Two. The specific calculation that\Noverflowed wasn't even
Dialogue: 10,0:00:03.27,0:00:07.35,Caption,,0,0,0,,needed after liftoff. It was a leftover,\Na routine that
Dialogue: 10,0:00:07.35,0:00:11.44,Caption,,0,0,0,,only mattered on the launch pad, left\Nrunning into flight
Dialogue: 10,0:00:11.44,0:00:15.52,Caption,,0,0,0,,for a rocket where it served no purpose\Nat all.
Dialogue: 10,0:00:15.52,0:00:17.16,Caption,,0,0,0,,Dead code, still armed.
Dialogue: 10,0:00:17.50,0:00:21.53,Caption,,0,0,0,,Three. That conversion had no protection\Non it — no
Dialogue: 10,0:00:21.53,0:00:25.57,Caption,,0,0,0,,check to catch a number that was too\Nlarge, no
Dialogue: 10,0:00:25.57,0:00:29.20,Caption,,0,0,0,,safe fallback. Some values in the system\Nwere protected.
Dialogue: 10,0:00:29.20,0:00:32.43,Caption,,0,0,0,,This one was deliberately left\Nunprotected, to save
Dialogue: 10,0:00:32.43,0:00:36.06,Caption,,0,0,0,,processing power, based on an assumption\Nthat the number
Dialogue: 10,0:00:36.06,0:00:40.10,Caption,,0,0,0,,could never get that big. On Ariane 4,\Nthat assumption
Dialogue: 10,0:00:40.10,0:00:43.73,Caption,,0,0,0,,was true. On Ariane 5, no one re-checked\Nit.
